{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:41:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:41:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14289"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14289"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.53,0.32,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6984"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78394"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old Aboriginal man presents to Alice Springs Hospital Emergency Department with a productive cough of 3 weeks duration. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 114/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. A chest x-ray is shown below. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following precautions should be adopted and what mask should be worn when reviewing this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact precautions + N95 mask","Droplet precautions + Surgical mask","Airborne precautions + N95 mask","Droplet precautions + N95 mask","Airborne precautions + Surgical mask"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for pulmonary tuberculosis (TB), including prolonged productive cough, fever, and the changes seen on the chest X-ray. The patient\u0027s Aboriginal background and location in Central Australia also increase the pre-test probability of TB. Given these features, appropriate infection control measures are crucial. Notification to the local public health unit/centre for disease control is also essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAirborne precautions + N95 mask\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct combination for suspected pulmonary TB. \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E is transmitted via small airborne particles (droplet nuclei) that can remain suspended in the air for prolonged periods. N95 masks provide the necessary filtration of these particles, while airborne precautions include placement in a negative pressure room and limiting patient movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptions: \u003Cstrong\u003EContact precautions + N95 mask \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Edroplet precautions + N95 mask\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst the N95 mask is the correct mask to be worn, contact precautions and droplet precautions are inadequate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOptions: \u003Cstrong\u003EDroplet precautions\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E+ Surgical mask\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EAirborne precautions + Surgical mask\u003C/strong\u003E. These options are incorrect as an N95 mask is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersonal protective equipment under contact precautions generally only includes gloves and gown. Contact precautions are appropriate for conditions such as gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDroplet precautions are adopted for patients with suspected or confirmed infections with pathogens transmitted by respiratory droplets, which are generated by a patient who is coughing, sneezing or talking. A surgical mask is required but generally not an N95 mask for these conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersonal protective equipment under airborne precautions includes a fit-tested N95 mask or higher level respirator. Airborne precautions should be adopted for patients with conditions such as tuberculosis, chicken pox, measles and disseminated herpes zoster.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Airborne precautions with N95 mask are required for suspected pulmonary tuberculosis.","Key features suggesting pulmonary tuberculosis include prolonged productive cough, fever, and upper lobe changes on chest x-ray.","Indigenous Australians living in Central Australia have higher rates of tuberculosis compared to non-Indigenous Australians."],"references":["Transmission-Based Precautions. In: CDC Infection Control [Online]. Available from: https://www.cdc.gov/infection-control/hcp/basics/transmission-based-precautions.html","Tuberculosis (TB). In: Northern Territory Government | NT Health [Online]. Available from: https://health.nt.gov.au/public-health-notifiable-diseases/tuberculosis-tb"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78394"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14289"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21798"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21798","l